WEBVTT

00:08.459 --> 00:10.461
[wind gusting]

00:34.485 --> 00:37.488
♪

01:07.866 --> 01:10.086
♪

01:38.157 --> 01:40.377
♪

02:04.096 --> 02:06.925
[bird squawking]

02:14.759 --> 02:17.109
[muffled thumping]

02:22.767 --> 02:24.334
[thumping continues]

02:25.944 --> 02:28.599
[groans]
Six fucking hours!

02:28.773 --> 02:30.949
I had to piss in my shoe.

02:34.561 --> 02:36.607
[pants]
Where are we?

02:38.261 --> 02:40.132
Pluto.

02:41.438 --> 02:43.135
So tell me again.

02:43.309 --> 02:44.615
He came to see you.

02:44.789 --> 02:46.269
He needed guns.

02:46.443 --> 02:48.401
They're gonna kill all of youse.
You know that, right?

02:48.575 --> 02:50.447
Calamita.
Tell me again,

02:50.621 --> 02:52.884
or I'll tie you to the bumper
and you can run.

02:53.058 --> 02:54.712
J-Jesus.

02:54.886 --> 02:56.540
He-he came looking
for some hardware--

02:56.714 --> 02:59.456
uh, rifles, pistols--
said he was hitting the road,

02:59.630 --> 03:01.806
he had to kill some people
i-in Kansas.

03:01.980 --> 03:03.895
Kansas is a state.

03:04.069 --> 03:06.071
Like I said,
Liberty or-or Liberal.

03:06.245 --> 03:07.768
Who has he got to kill?

03:07.942 --> 03:10.510
I don't know.
A Swede? An Irishman?

03:10.684 --> 03:13.470
Now, shit, boy,
can I get out of the damn trunk?

03:13.644 --> 03:15.298
Don't... No! God!

03:37.494 --> 03:39.322
[engine turns off]

03:49.506 --> 03:51.725
You ever meet you a Korean?

03:51.899 --> 03:53.161
Say again?

03:53.336 --> 03:56.469
I ain't never met me no Korean.

03:56.643 --> 03:59.167
But Truman says I ought to send
my junior over there

03:59.342 --> 04:00.517
to shoot some.

04:03.259 --> 04:05.261
Met a lady from Thailand once.

04:05.435 --> 04:07.567
I'm not sure
what you'd call her.

04:07.741 --> 04:11.049
Radio said blue skies, but...

04:11.223 --> 04:13.660
my hips are screaming rain.

04:13.834 --> 04:16.315
You seen an Italian fella
come through here?

04:16.489 --> 04:18.709
Real skeletal-looking.

04:18.883 --> 04:21.146
Wears a red coat?

04:21.320 --> 04:24.149
Mostly we get farmers
round this way,

04:24.323 --> 04:26.978
folks on their way
to Salvation Methodist

04:27.152 --> 04:29.720
or Consecrated Lutheran.

04:29.894 --> 04:33.201
Em and Henry give ten percent
off all soda pop

04:33.376 --> 04:35.203
if you pay with a Bible quote.

04:35.378 --> 04:36.640
This'd be yesterday,

04:36.814 --> 04:38.859
maybe this morning.

04:39.033 --> 04:41.645
-[thumping from trunk]
-Can't be that far ahead of me.

04:41.819 --> 04:43.081
[muffled]:
Hey, hey. Hey.

04:43.255 --> 04:45.170
What are we stopping for?
Let's go.

04:45.344 --> 04:46.345
Hey.

04:46.519 --> 04:47.651
-[thumping]
-Hey!

04:47.825 --> 04:48.913
Son...

04:49.087 --> 04:50.784
ain't my business,

04:50.958 --> 04:54.571
but are you at all concerned
about that ruckus in your trunk?

04:54.745 --> 04:56.181
-[thumping]
-Let's go.

04:56.355 --> 04:57.574
-Nope.
-Hey.

04:57.748 --> 04:59.924
Don't leave me in here.

05:00.098 --> 05:03.188
Well, we the only
filling station for a good hop,

05:03.362 --> 05:05.408
so if that fella's coming
this way,

05:05.582 --> 05:07.627
we gonna see him by and by.

05:15.461 --> 05:18.682
Mind if I pull around back
and wait?

05:20.118 --> 05:22.250
Well, Em and Henry
are at church.

05:22.425 --> 05:24.949
Like I said,
they real religious.

05:25.123 --> 05:28.300
Don't usually see 'em
till evenings on Sundays.

05:28.474 --> 05:31.782
Still, ain't supposed
to dawdle with strangers.

05:31.956 --> 05:33.958
[Willy spits]

05:39.964 --> 05:41.966
[thumping from trunk]

05:42.140 --> 05:44.621
I could help you get
these walls painted.

05:44.795 --> 05:47.058
[thumping continues]

05:47.232 --> 05:49.234
If by "help,"
you mean buy me a Nehi

05:49.408 --> 05:51.541
and pull me up a chair
while youwork,

05:51.715 --> 05:53.499
then you're on.

05:54.979 --> 05:58.374
-[thumping]
-ALDO: Hey. Where'd you go?

05:59.418 --> 06:00.767
[car door opens]

06:00.941 --> 06:03.727
-[groaning]
-[car rumbling]

06:09.689 --> 06:10.821
[grunts]

06:10.995 --> 06:13.476
-[panting]
-[engine turns off]

06:13.650 --> 06:14.781
[car door opens]

06:14.955 --> 06:16.914
[car door closes]

06:22.833 --> 06:24.138
Come on.

06:24.312 --> 06:25.879
We got work to do.

06:26.053 --> 06:27.577
W-What kind of work?

06:28.665 --> 06:30.101
Gonna paint this building.

06:30.275 --> 06:32.669
♪ Will that family circle here♪

06:32.843 --> 06:35.454
♪ Be unbroken over there♪

06:35.628 --> 06:37.674
♪ Will that circle be unbroken♪

06:37.848 --> 06:39.806
♪ In the sky, in the sky♪

06:39.980 --> 06:42.374
♪ Will that family circle here♪

06:42.548 --> 06:44.724
♪ Be unbroken over there♪

06:44.898 --> 06:47.988
♪ Will that circle be unbroken
by and by♪

06:48.162 --> 06:49.642
♪ By and by♪

06:49.816 --> 06:51.775
♪ Well, I have a mother
and a father♪

06:51.949 --> 06:53.733
♪ Sister and a brother, too♪

06:53.907 --> 06:56.388
♪ Well, I have friends
and other relations♪

06:56.562 --> 06:58.521
♪ With whom I used to know♪

06:58.695 --> 07:00.914
♪ Well, they're sitting
down in the kingdom♪

07:01.088 --> 07:02.960
♪ They're a-waitin'
there for me♪

07:03.134 --> 07:05.266
♪ Now, when they call
the family reunion♪

07:05.441 --> 07:07.355
-♪ I'll be there♪
-♪ I'll be there♪

07:07.530 --> 07:09.401
♪ Yes, I'll be there♪

07:09.575 --> 07:12.099
♪ Ooh, I'll be there♪

07:12.273 --> 07:14.667
♪ When they call
the family reunion♪

07:14.841 --> 07:16.756
♪ I'll be there, I'll be there♪

07:16.930 --> 07:18.497
-♪ Will the circle♪
-[thunder rumbling]

07:18.671 --> 07:20.543
♪ Circle be unbroken♪

07:20.717 --> 07:22.414
♪ Now, will the circle♪

07:22.588 --> 07:25.069
♪ Be unbroken by and by♪

07:25.243 --> 07:27.898
♪ By and by.♪

07:35.993 --> 07:38.561
Go right ahead, Your Majesty.

07:40.693 --> 07:42.260
[drops coin in slot]

07:46.656 --> 07:50.224
You boys really think
you can run things?

07:50.398 --> 07:52.836
White man called
my daddy "boy" once.

07:53.924 --> 07:56.274
He ended up with wooden teeth,

07:56.448 --> 07:58.058
just like George Washington.

07:58.232 --> 07:59.451
Yeah, yeah.

08:02.236 --> 08:04.195
Personally...

08:04.369 --> 08:06.893
I'm all for you coloreds
breaking even.

08:07.067 --> 08:09.200
I mean, why should the bosses
get all the fat

08:09.374 --> 08:11.202
when we're the ones
down in the mud

08:11.376 --> 08:14.118
-scrounging for dimes?
-Oh.

08:14.292 --> 08:16.163
So you're one of us now?

08:16.337 --> 08:17.600
[chuckles]

08:17.774 --> 08:19.776
No, I'm not saying that.

08:19.950 --> 08:21.429
Just...

08:21.604 --> 08:23.431
Say there's a turtle.

08:23.606 --> 08:24.911
Turtle?

08:25.085 --> 08:26.652
Mm, king turtle.

08:26.826 --> 08:29.307
He rules over
everything he sees.

08:29.481 --> 08:31.439
Except he's a turtle,
so he's real low

08:31.614 --> 08:33.746
-to the ground.
-I'm gonna put you
back in the trunk.

08:33.920 --> 08:34.965
No, no.

08:35.139 --> 08:37.620
Hear me out.

08:37.794 --> 08:39.839
So, this king turtle,
he calls two of his guys

08:40.013 --> 08:41.928
and he tells them
to climb on top of each other,

08:42.102 --> 08:43.451
you know, like a ladder.

08:43.626 --> 08:45.671
And he climbs on their backs.

08:45.845 --> 08:49.327
So now he can see further
but still just, like, 50 feet.

08:49.501 --> 08:51.851
So he calls even more turtles.

08:52.025 --> 08:55.289
And one by one,
they get on top of each other.

08:55.463 --> 08:57.683
And up he goes.

08:57.857 --> 09:00.294
Till all the turtles
are in a pile.

09:00.468 --> 09:01.992
And old king turtle--

09:02.166 --> 09:04.298
oh, he can see for miles.

09:04.472 --> 09:06.605
Except...

09:06.779 --> 09:08.912
the guys on the bottom...

09:09.086 --> 09:11.044
are getting crushed.

09:12.698 --> 09:15.571
-[vehicle approaching]
-And I'm saying...

09:15.745 --> 09:17.660
♪

09:23.666 --> 09:25.668
[brakes squeak]

09:34.154 --> 09:36.113
♪

09:50.040 --> 09:52.042
♪

10:15.021 --> 10:16.980
♪

10:45.225 --> 10:47.184
♪

11:05.724 --> 11:07.813
JOSEPH McCARTHY [over radio]:
Today we are engaged

11:07.987 --> 11:09.467
in the final, all-out battle

11:09.641 --> 11:11.469
between communistic atheism

11:11.643 --> 11:13.819
and democratic Christianity.

11:13.993 --> 11:15.778
The modern champions
of communism

11:15.952 --> 11:18.041
have selected this as the time.

11:18.215 --> 11:20.957
And, folks, the chips are down. They are truly down.

11:21.131 --> 11:23.002
"When a great democracy
is destroyed,

11:23.176 --> 11:25.004
"it will not be
from enemies from without,

11:25.178 --> 11:28.355
but rather because of enemies
from within."

11:28.529 --> 11:30.488
I have here in my hands

11:30.662 --> 11:32.490
a list of 205 names

11:32.664 --> 11:33.970
that were made known
to the Secretary...

11:34.144 --> 11:35.536
[radio clicks off]

11:37.538 --> 11:39.976
How much farther?

11:40.150 --> 11:42.805
Hours, not days.

12:02.172 --> 12:04.174
SATCHEL:
What is it?

12:05.175 --> 12:08.004
Someplace to kip.

12:08.178 --> 12:10.180
Couple of nights.

12:10.354 --> 12:12.356
Get our heads on straight.

12:20.668 --> 12:22.714
[wind whistling]

12:42.647 --> 12:44.649
[wind whistling]

12:56.226 --> 12:58.054
What's that smell?

12:59.446 --> 13:01.753
Fresh air.

13:11.067 --> 13:13.286
SATCHEL:
What does it say?

13:13.460 --> 13:16.507
Sleep with one eye open.

13:16.681 --> 13:18.248
Huh?

13:22.426 --> 13:24.428
[coughing in distance]

13:27.431 --> 13:30.216
MILLIGAN:
We'll be needing a room
for a night or two.

13:30.390 --> 13:32.697
Plymouth Rock or Sutter's Mill?

13:32.871 --> 13:34.786
What?

13:34.960 --> 13:36.788
Things work a specific way
around here,

13:36.962 --> 13:38.398
so I got to figure out
where to put you.

13:38.572 --> 13:41.271
Plymouth Rock or Sutter's Mill?

13:41.445 --> 13:43.142
MILLIGAN:
Well,

13:43.316 --> 13:46.276
that's in California, yeah?

13:46.450 --> 13:48.452
McCarthy or Eisenhower?

13:48.626 --> 13:50.889
Oh, we don't follow politics.

13:51.063 --> 13:53.109
Eisenhower it is.

13:54.110 --> 13:56.025
Uh, lastly...

13:56.199 --> 13:58.897
Old Testament or New?

13:59.071 --> 14:02.466
Which is the one where
you get to be born again?

14:02.640 --> 14:04.381
That'd be the New.

14:04.555 --> 14:07.558
West side it is.

14:07.732 --> 14:09.603
Any bags?

14:09.777 --> 14:12.041
No.

14:12.215 --> 14:14.608
-He your valet?
-We take care of each other.

14:14.782 --> 14:16.306
Hmm.

14:16.480 --> 14:19.004
The sisters don't much care
for colored folk.

14:19.178 --> 14:22.834
-"Sisters" as in nuns?
-No. As in sisters.

14:23.008 --> 14:26.316
Picola and Iola Crumb.
They the owners.

14:26.490 --> 14:28.274
And like I said,

14:28.448 --> 14:31.103
they don't care much
for coloreds.

14:31.277 --> 14:33.497
I understand.
Come on, kid.

14:33.671 --> 14:37.196
-We'll find someplace else.
-Now, hold on.

14:37.370 --> 14:38.676
Didn't say they had a rule.

14:38.850 --> 14:40.852
Just said
they don't care for us.

14:41.026 --> 14:42.985
Steer clear of them,
you'll be right as rain.

14:43.159 --> 14:45.857
Come on.
I'll give you the tour.

14:47.859 --> 14:50.035
This is the sitting room,

14:50.209 --> 14:53.647
for board games
and conversating.

14:53.821 --> 14:55.693
[quietly]:
Mm-hmm.

15:03.179 --> 15:05.137
What's with the line everyplace?

15:05.311 --> 15:08.445
Well, now, the sisters,
they ain't got along

15:08.619 --> 15:10.273
since the Dust Bowl days.

15:10.447 --> 15:13.145
But neither will renounce
their claim to the premises,

15:13.319 --> 15:16.018
so I ask y'all questions,
and given your answers,

15:16.192 --> 15:18.890
you either go west or east.

15:19.064 --> 15:20.892
Why east or west?

15:21.066 --> 15:22.938
Why any one thing or the other?

15:23.112 --> 15:25.636
Just is the way it is.

15:25.810 --> 15:27.812
[man coughing]

15:33.600 --> 15:35.689
INA:
This is you and the boy.

15:35.863 --> 15:38.257
[coughing]

15:38.431 --> 15:40.651
MILLIGAN:
Hey.

15:47.919 --> 15:49.703
Bathroom's down the hall.

15:49.877 --> 15:51.575
Towels in the armoire.

15:51.749 --> 15:53.751
You need anything else,
we probably ain't got it,

15:53.925 --> 15:55.883
-but it don't hurt to ask.
-[coughing in distance]

15:56.058 --> 15:58.582
-SATCHEL: I'm hungry.
-Well, they put supper
on the table

15:58.756 --> 16:00.062
at 5:00 each night.

16:00.236 --> 16:02.586
Fish sticks,
maybe even some potatoes.

16:02.760 --> 16:04.414
Green beans from a can.

16:04.588 --> 16:08.244
It ain't much, but it's better
than boiling your shoes.

16:09.767 --> 16:11.769
[coughing in distance]

16:20.256 --> 16:22.432
I call this one.

16:25.522 --> 16:27.437
I saw some books in the den.

16:27.611 --> 16:29.395
You can read up here
till I get back.

16:29.569 --> 16:30.744
[match strikes]

16:30.918 --> 16:32.616
Where are you going?

16:32.790 --> 16:35.662
If we're gonna hide
and stay hidden, we need money.

16:35.836 --> 16:37.664
[exhales sharply]

16:37.838 --> 16:40.798
It so happens
I laid some away in town.

16:42.060 --> 16:45.759
I've got to retrieve it, alone.

16:45.933 --> 16:49.546
But-but there's a hospital man
next door,

16:49.720 --> 16:51.287
all bandaged up.

16:54.116 --> 16:56.596
A man's a man.

16:56.770 --> 17:00.209
If you can't run,
just do like we practiced.

17:00.383 --> 17:03.560
Thigh, stomach, chest.

17:05.040 --> 17:07.694
-Can't I ride with you?
-No. Remember,

17:07.868 --> 17:10.654
if I don't come back,
I'm dead or in jail.

17:21.969 --> 17:23.145
[knife clicks]

17:41.511 --> 17:43.861
-[car door closes]
-[engine starts]

17:56.830 --> 17:58.876
Shit.

18:00.921 --> 18:02.923
[engine turns off]

18:07.189 --> 18:10.061
You can see in here,
this is frost-resistant,

18:10.235 --> 18:11.497
so you don't get it
on your food.

18:11.671 --> 18:12.933
Let me tell you a little
about Kenmore...

18:13.108 --> 18:15.066
I'll be with you
in a moment, pal.

18:15.240 --> 18:18.852
Now, Kenmore is all about
freedom from your cooking cares.

18:19.026 --> 18:21.507
-I'll have to ask my husband.
-Oh, all right.

18:21.681 --> 18:23.466
-You want to take
a catalog, ma'am?
-No.

18:23.640 --> 18:26.077
All right.
Have a good day.

18:26.251 --> 18:27.731
[sighs]

18:27.905 --> 18:30.386
Happy New Year,
uh, in anticipation.

18:30.560 --> 18:32.605
What happened to the feed store?

18:32.779 --> 18:34.912
Well, now, old Miss Gingerly,
you know, her three boys

18:35.086 --> 18:38.568
all passed in the Great War,
so, desolate with grief,

18:38.742 --> 18:40.874
she, uh, turned over operations
to her brother Virgil,

18:41.048 --> 18:43.877
and he promptly gambled away
the family fortune.

18:44.051 --> 18:46.750
[laughs softly]

18:48.273 --> 18:50.971
There, uh,
used to be a wall here.

18:52.712 --> 18:55.150
Well, yeah...

18:56.542 --> 18:58.544
Yes, sir, yeah, yeah, there did.

18:59.937 --> 19:02.069
Can I interest you
in a dinette set?

19:02.244 --> 19:05.421
Maybe a "dee-van"
for your boudoir? [chuckles]

19:09.686 --> 19:11.122
You the new owner?

19:11.296 --> 19:13.429
Yes, sir.
Beachwood Indiana.

19:13.603 --> 19:15.082
Me and my brother Haskell,
the younger,

19:15.257 --> 19:17.433
we, uh, bought the place
at auction.

19:17.607 --> 19:19.043
[phone ringing]

19:24.875 --> 19:26.964
Oh, now...
[chuckles]

19:27.138 --> 19:29.445
Just when we was
starting to hit it off.

19:29.619 --> 19:30.837
Uh, back in a jiff.

19:31.011 --> 19:32.970
[soft thud]

19:35.015 --> 19:38.105
[in distance]:
T. Woodman Catalog Store.

19:38.280 --> 19:40.630
Yes, uh, yeah, yeah, yeah.

19:40.804 --> 19:42.588
[continues indistinctly]

19:42.762 --> 19:45.635
♪

19:45.809 --> 19:46.766
All right.

19:46.940 --> 19:49.073
You, too.

19:49.247 --> 19:50.770
[hangs up phone]

19:50.944 --> 19:52.903
All righty, then...

19:56.733 --> 19:58.604
[sighs]

19:58.778 --> 20:00.606
[coughing, laughter in distance]

20:00.780 --> 20:02.739
[indistinct chatter in distance]

20:20.322 --> 20:23.107
[thump, rattling]

20:26.850 --> 20:28.330
[scratching]

20:30.767 --> 20:31.942
[scratching continues]

20:41.343 --> 20:42.561
[scratching continues]

21:01.145 --> 21:03.365
[hinge squeaks]

21:03.539 --> 21:05.236
-[barks]
-[gasps]

21:07.194 --> 21:09.327
[whines]

21:09.501 --> 21:11.460
[dog panting]

21:16.334 --> 21:18.249
[whining]

21:18.423 --> 21:21.818
[whispering]:
Hey, come on. Come on, girl.

21:24.995 --> 21:25.822
[whining]

21:25.996 --> 21:27.563
Good girl.

21:33.003 --> 21:35.222
Rabbit?
Is that your name?

21:35.397 --> 21:36.920
[barks]

21:44.623 --> 21:45.929
[Rabbit scratching door]

21:49.019 --> 21:50.194
-[barking]
-Wait. Wait up.

21:50.368 --> 21:51.674
Come on, girl.

21:51.848 --> 21:53.284
-[barks]
-[woman shouting in distance]

21:57.462 --> 21:59.595
-Hey. Come on, girl.
-[barks]

22:00.944 --> 22:03.294
Wait. Wait.

22:14.349 --> 22:16.699
Well, now we got a secret,
you and me.

22:17.787 --> 22:19.049
How's that?

22:19.223 --> 22:22.922
The sisters can't abide spirits
of any kind.

22:23.096 --> 22:25.055
Alcohol, I'm saying.

22:25.229 --> 22:27.231
I know what spirits are.

22:27.405 --> 22:29.102
East or west?

22:29.276 --> 22:30.887
Huh? Oh.

22:31.061 --> 22:32.758
West?

22:32.932 --> 22:34.891
You best step to this side
of the line, then,

22:35.065 --> 22:37.023
in case they're watching.

22:42.420 --> 22:44.074
Hunk Swindell's the name.

22:44.248 --> 22:47.294
Aluminum siding's the game.
[chuckles]

22:47.469 --> 22:48.774
That your canine?

22:48.948 --> 22:50.472
I found her upstairs.

22:50.646 --> 22:52.387
Hm.

22:52.561 --> 22:54.127
Ask me a question.

22:54.301 --> 22:56.739
-What?
-Dale Carnegie.

22:56.913 --> 22:58.654
How to Win Friends
and Influence People.

22:58.828 --> 23:00.525
"Six Ways
to Make People Like You."

23:00.699 --> 23:04.268
Number one: become genuinely
interested in other people.

23:04.442 --> 23:06.226
So ask me a question.

23:06.401 --> 23:08.490
Um... you got any food?

23:08.664 --> 23:11.841
[laughs]

23:12.015 --> 23:14.191
Make 'em laugh.

23:14.365 --> 23:15.671
Yeah, that's rule number nine.

23:15.845 --> 23:18.413
Hard to dislike a man
what's got a funny bone.

23:18.587 --> 23:22.112
Me, I got two. Plus the gift
of gab, ever since I was a boy.

23:22.286 --> 23:24.027
But it wasn't till
I found Mr. Carnegie

23:24.201 --> 23:26.159
that I really learned
to channel my thoughts into

23:26.333 --> 23:27.509
a strategy for success.

23:27.683 --> 23:29.380
[footsteps approaching]

23:30.381 --> 23:32.209
Who's this now?

23:32.383 --> 23:34.037
Ain't got a name, I don't think.

23:34.211 --> 23:35.691
I'm just calling him "boy."

23:37.040 --> 23:38.824
You ain't from Texas, by chance?

23:38.998 --> 23:42.001
No, sir.

23:42.175 --> 23:45.527
Oil fields as far
as the eye can see, I heard.

23:45.701 --> 23:47.703
Instant millions.

23:47.877 --> 23:50.401
All you got to do
is get off the train.

23:50.575 --> 23:52.142
-That's where I'm headed.
-HUNK: Yeah.

23:52.316 --> 23:54.840
My new friend's got a bit
of gold rush fever.

23:55.014 --> 23:56.668
[scoffs]
Better than knocking on doors

23:56.842 --> 23:58.627
with nothing
but a briefcase and a smile.

23:58.801 --> 24:00.106
HUNK:
Ain't nothing in this world

24:00.280 --> 24:02.021
impossible if'n
a man's got the right attitude.

24:02.195 --> 24:03.632
[laughs]

24:03.806 --> 24:05.634
[footsteps approaching]

24:05.808 --> 24:07.723
Said stay in the room.

24:07.897 --> 24:09.986
SATCHEL:
But the dog got out.

24:10.160 --> 24:11.727
Whose dog?

24:13.206 --> 24:15.252
Mine.

24:21.737 --> 24:23.739
[footsteps receding]

24:26.263 --> 24:28.221
MILLIGAN:
We've had a setback.

24:29.266 --> 24:31.834
Things ain't the way I left 'em.

24:32.008 --> 24:34.750
Which... Only a fool thinks

24:34.924 --> 24:37.448
the world's gonna
stay exactly as it was.

24:39.406 --> 24:41.757
So there's that.

24:46.457 --> 24:50.287
But I worked the problem,
and I think... I got a solve.

24:51.375 --> 24:53.072
I think she likes me.

24:53.246 --> 24:55.118
I'm glad you're having
such a nice day,

24:55.292 --> 24:57.468
but I don't want you wandering
the place while I'm gone.

25:02.647 --> 25:05.345
Last thing we need
is unwanted attention.

25:07.434 --> 25:08.740
[bell clanging]

25:08.914 --> 25:10.916
INA:
Come and get it while it's hot.

25:11.090 --> 25:12.265
-Wait. That...
-[barks]

25:12.439 --> 25:13.832
Hey.

25:14.006 --> 25:15.268
[barks, growls]

25:15.442 --> 25:16.792
Stay.

25:16.966 --> 25:19.185
[bell continues clanging]

25:19.359 --> 25:20.796
[growls softly]

25:20.970 --> 25:22.319
-[door closes]  -HUNK: My name's Hunk Swindell.

25:22.493 --> 25:23.494
This is Hickory J. Milch.

25:23.668 --> 25:24.930
And you're...

25:25.104 --> 25:26.802
-Uh, Pastor Roanoke.
-Pastor Roanoke.

25:26.976 --> 25:28.934
Very good, and, uh, this is...

25:29.108 --> 25:31.415
No coloreds at the table.

25:31.589 --> 25:33.112
What?

25:33.286 --> 25:35.506
I said,
no coloreds at the table.

25:35.680 --> 25:39.292
[laughs]
My side, my rules.

25:39.466 --> 25:41.730
-Sit down, sweetie.
-What?

25:41.904 --> 25:44.341
HUNK:
Hey, glad you could join us.

25:44.515 --> 25:45.995
We were just going around
the room, doing introductions.

25:46.169 --> 25:48.867
Uh, you met myself
and young Hickory.

25:49.041 --> 25:51.304
Uh, on the east side,
there's Pastor Roanoke

25:51.478 --> 25:53.959
-and his wife.
-Mother.

25:54.133 --> 25:56.005
Mother.

25:56.179 --> 25:58.616
And across from them,
uh, that's the Major,

25:58.790 --> 26:01.663
hero of Wounded Knee, and his...

26:01.837 --> 26:04.274
Uh, Millie is my niece.

26:06.537 --> 26:08.713
So now you know who weare.

26:11.716 --> 26:13.022
Uh, the name's Duffy.

26:13.196 --> 26:16.199
And this is my ward, Colt.

26:16.373 --> 26:18.636
-What?
-Said he's an Irishman

26:18.810 --> 26:20.769
and the Negro is his ward.

26:22.553 --> 26:23.685
Say the blessing already.

26:23.859 --> 26:25.556
Food's getting cold.

26:30.561 --> 26:32.389
Almighty Father, we pray Thee,

26:32.563 --> 26:35.174
sanctify this food
that it may strengthen us

26:35.348 --> 26:38.874
to do and endure Thy Holy Will.

26:39.048 --> 26:41.398
[clears throat] Here's
a good one that can't fail.

26:41.572 --> 26:43.618
Lord Jesus, hear our prayers

26:43.792 --> 26:45.663
and bless us with Thy bounty

26:45.837 --> 26:47.839
in this life and the next,
for where there is risk,

26:48.013 --> 26:50.320
there is always reward.

26:50.494 --> 26:52.844
Amen.

26:53.018 --> 26:55.455
What kind of cockamamie blessing
is that?

26:55.630 --> 26:56.892
HICKORY:
Prayer for prosperity.

26:57.066 --> 26:58.502
ROANOKE:
Son,

26:58.676 --> 27:00.069
that ain't how you talk to God.

27:00.243 --> 27:02.071
It's how we conversate with Him
out West.

27:02.245 --> 27:04.247
Heathens.

27:11.297 --> 27:13.473
So, Duffy, what brings you
to this neck of the woods?

27:13.648 --> 27:17.086
I heard there was some
honest work up at Sioux Falls.

27:18.957 --> 27:20.655
Planning to make
a fresh start of it.

27:20.829 --> 27:22.395
MAJOR:
Well, that's damn peculiar,

27:22.569 --> 27:24.267
if you ask me.

27:24.441 --> 27:26.486
White man traveling
with a Negro child.

27:26.661 --> 27:28.097
What?

27:28.271 --> 27:30.577
Said he don't much care
for colored folk.

27:30.752 --> 27:32.014
IOLA:
Oh...

27:32.188 --> 27:34.451
What line of work you in,
partner?

27:34.625 --> 27:36.105
You ask a lot of questions.

27:36.279 --> 27:38.107
Guilty as charged.

27:38.281 --> 27:40.283
Dale Carnegie, rule number one.
[chuckles]

27:40.457 --> 27:42.764
But I'll lay off you.

27:45.592 --> 27:47.986
-Mm-hmm?
-Tell me a story, Seymour.

27:48.160 --> 27:50.728
Well, which one do you want,
sugar plum?

27:50.902 --> 27:53.513
Uh, let's see.
Hansel and Gretel.

27:53.688 --> 27:55.602
Or would you like
the legend of Goldilocks?

27:55.777 --> 27:57.082
[both laugh]

27:57.256 --> 27:58.475
Hey, funny you mention that.

27:58.649 --> 28:00.216
I was talking
to a fella on the train,

28:00.390 --> 28:03.436
must've been, um, winter last,
works in publishing.

28:03.610 --> 28:05.438
Did you know
that in the original Goldilocks,

28:05.612 --> 28:07.223
it was witches, not bears?

28:07.397 --> 28:10.052
In any case, he tells me,

28:10.226 --> 28:12.097
think about this poor girl,

28:12.271 --> 28:15.318
no home of her own,
just wandering the woods.

28:15.492 --> 28:17.146
This fella said
that to his mind,

28:17.320 --> 28:18.713
Goldilocks
is the classic example

28:18.887 --> 28:21.280
of an outsider
in search of himself.

28:22.934 --> 28:25.502
If you think about it,
the story's got no ending.

28:25.676 --> 28:28.200
I mean, the bears--
they get justice--

28:28.374 --> 28:31.116
chasing an intruder out
of their home, but for the girl?

28:31.290 --> 28:33.945
Well, she's back out
in the cold.

28:34.119 --> 28:36.643
No family, no home.

28:36.818 --> 28:38.994
Doesn't fit in anywhere.

29:00.058 --> 29:02.017
♪

29:24.691 --> 29:26.128
[Rabbit whining]

29:26.302 --> 29:28.130
I thought I said
leave the dog in the room.

29:28.304 --> 29:30.915
She'll get lonely
and she'll bark,

29:31.089 --> 29:33.962
and that's
unwanted attention, right?

29:34.136 --> 29:35.877
Right?

29:38.705 --> 29:40.751
[Rabbit whining]

29:42.274 --> 29:44.233
[engine starts]

29:52.502 --> 29:56.201
-The future is what?
-How's that?

29:56.375 --> 29:59.596
What's it gonna say?

29:59.770 --> 30:01.990
Wait till it's finished.
Then you'll see.

30:04.557 --> 30:08.213
Well... finish the damn thing
already.

30:08.387 --> 30:11.608
Moment I finish it,
I'm out of a job.

30:11.782 --> 30:14.393
Plus, what do you care?
It's just a sign.

30:14.567 --> 30:16.221
It's the principle,

30:16.395 --> 30:18.615
making people live
with uncertainty.

30:18.789 --> 30:20.399
It ain't right.

30:20.573 --> 30:23.620
Send a letter to your
congressman, you're so irate.

30:32.585 --> 30:34.283
ANNOUNCER [over radio]:
And in Kansas City today,

30:34.457 --> 30:36.372
the mayor is calling
for additional law enforcement

30:36.546 --> 30:38.809
as the war between organized
crime syndicates heats up,

30:38.983 --> 30:40.637
following yesterday's
deadly shoot-out

30:40.811 --> 30:41.768
at the Kelsey slaughterhouse.

30:41.943 --> 30:43.814
[radio clicks off]

30:55.130 --> 30:56.653
[Rabbit barks]

31:00.004 --> 31:01.223
[engine turns off]

31:03.312 --> 31:05.792
-Is this where your money is?
-Stay put.

31:05.967 --> 31:08.491
-Lock the doors
and don't talk to nobody.
-[Rabbit barks]

31:08.665 --> 31:11.059
-And quiet the mutt.
-[Rabbit whines]

31:23.680 --> 31:26.509
-You're being paranoid.
-You didn't see him.

31:26.683 --> 31:29.512
Like a poison pack
of cigarettes.

31:29.686 --> 31:31.514
He asked about the wall.

31:31.688 --> 31:34.343
Maybe he's just
an enemy to change.

31:34.517 --> 31:36.127
What's that supposed to mean?

31:36.301 --> 31:38.695
I'm saying, maybe he liked
things the way they were.

31:38.869 --> 31:40.697
[sighs]
You know, I've half a mind

31:40.871 --> 31:43.308
to drive over to the cemetery
and make Ma take back

31:43.482 --> 31:44.919
when she said
you was the smart one.

31:45.093 --> 31:47.660
Well, if this fella comes back,

31:47.834 --> 31:49.836
we'll show him.

31:50.011 --> 31:52.013
Show me what?

31:54.189 --> 31:57.583
Both of you in the office, now.

32:20.867 --> 32:22.695
You found something
that belongs to me.

32:22.869 --> 32:25.046
I don't know what
you're talking about.

32:27.352 --> 32:29.528
The money.
Where is it?

32:29.702 --> 32:30.703
What money?

32:30.877 --> 32:31.922
[grunts]

32:33.576 --> 32:34.881
Not gonna ask again.

32:35.056 --> 32:36.579
BEACHWOOD:
I-It's in the safe.

32:36.753 --> 32:38.276
What's left.

32:38.450 --> 32:40.757
Open it.

32:40.931 --> 32:43.238
M-Mister,
what were we supposed to do?

32:43.412 --> 32:44.717
A bag of money in the wall,

32:44.891 --> 32:46.241
opening a store
with mouths to feed.

32:46.415 --> 32:49.244
You-you thank the Lord,
is what you do.

32:49.418 --> 32:50.723
A-And count every dime.

32:50.897 --> 32:53.117
Not your money.

32:53.291 --> 32:55.728
We bought the store
as-is, mister.

32:55.902 --> 32:58.296
Leaky pipes, bag of money,
what have you.

32:58.470 --> 33:00.472
That's the American way.

33:19.926 --> 33:22.886
There was five grand in here.

33:29.545 --> 33:31.721
[Rabbit barks, whines]

33:34.115 --> 33:36.117
[barks]

33:47.432 --> 33:49.217
Boy, is this your car?

33:51.132 --> 33:52.742
You got a hearing problem
or something?

33:52.916 --> 33:54.309
[barking]

33:54.483 --> 33:55.832
What are you doing?

33:56.876 --> 33:59.749
J-Jus... Just waiting.

34:03.187 --> 34:05.059
For what?

34:08.323 --> 34:11.021
I got a wife.

34:14.503 --> 34:16.679
I... I ain't married yet.

34:16.853 --> 34:19.029
Who's gonna feed the dogs?

34:19.986 --> 34:21.075
Step out of the vehicle.

34:21.249 --> 34:22.032
[Rabbit whining]

34:22.206 --> 34:24.295
I didn't do anything.

34:24.469 --> 34:26.515
Come on, do it now.

34:28.952 --> 34:31.302
-I'm just waiting.
-I said out of the car.

34:31.476 --> 34:33.522
[Rabbit whining]

34:36.525 --> 34:38.440
-Now.
-[Rabbit barks]

34:38.614 --> 34:41.051
Quiet.

34:43.358 --> 34:44.533
Is there a problem, Officer?

34:44.707 --> 34:45.708
[Rabbit whining]

34:47.884 --> 34:50.060
-Is this your car?
-Yes, sir.

34:53.019 --> 34:54.456
He with you?

34:54.630 --> 34:56.545
Yes.

35:00.114 --> 35:03.073
-And what's your relation
to this kid?
-I'm his guardian.

35:05.945 --> 35:08.948
Who talked you into
that cockeyed arrangement?

35:09.123 --> 35:12.909
Well, now, I served
with his daddy in the war.

35:13.083 --> 35:14.476
Jerries killed him
on Armistice Day.

35:14.650 --> 35:15.738
Can you believe that?

35:17.566 --> 35:19.437
First man killed in peacetime.

35:19.611 --> 35:22.745
Least I could do was care
for his offspring.

35:29.752 --> 35:32.015
Well...

35:32.189 --> 35:33.408
you want my advice,

35:33.582 --> 35:35.236
you gonna travel
with a colored kid

35:35.410 --> 35:37.020
in a town like this...

35:37.194 --> 35:39.022
just keep him out of sight.

35:40.241 --> 35:41.546
Yes, sir.

35:41.720 --> 35:44.941
Appreciate that.
It's, uh, all new to me.

36:13.796 --> 36:15.798
I'm hungry.

36:15.972 --> 36:17.974
Supper's in an hour.

36:19.454 --> 36:21.760
Maybe they got something
in the kitchen.

36:21.934 --> 36:24.110
I could look.

36:24.285 --> 36:26.722
I've changed my mind.

36:26.896 --> 36:28.811
We're leaving tonight.

36:28.985 --> 36:31.379
-After the meal.
-Can I bring Rabbit?

36:31.553 --> 36:33.816
-No.
-Why not?

36:33.990 --> 36:35.339
'Cause I said so.

36:35.513 --> 36:37.123
Don't need
another mouth to feed,

36:37.298 --> 36:38.516
and she's always barking.

36:38.690 --> 36:40.257
But I could teach her
to be quiet.

36:40.431 --> 36:41.998
I said no.

36:50.093 --> 36:52.356
What's that about?

36:52.530 --> 36:55.272
-I just wanted one thing.
-One thing?

36:55.446 --> 36:57.405
Huh, what are you on about?

37:01.278 --> 37:04.281
One thing for my birthday.

37:04.455 --> 37:05.413
Your...

37:05.587 --> 37:07.197
What?

37:09.852 --> 37:12.115
When the hell is your birthday?

37:13.116 --> 37:14.726
Today.

37:30.873 --> 37:32.701
Hey.
You wouldn't happen to have

37:32.875 --> 37:36.618
a cupcake or a candy bar
or something?

37:36.792 --> 37:38.359
For the kid.

37:38.533 --> 37:40.709
It's his birthday, see,
and I didn't know, and...

37:40.883 --> 37:43.842
Mm-mmm, no, the sisters
don't believe in sugar.

37:44.016 --> 37:45.844
But there's a filling station

37:46.018 --> 37:47.977
eight or nine miles
down the road.

37:48.151 --> 37:49.979
Probably get him a cupcake

37:50.153 --> 37:52.329
or candy bar or something there.

37:52.503 --> 37:53.678
[sniffs]

37:53.852 --> 37:55.289
Thanks.

37:58.466 --> 38:01.556
If the kid
comes looking for me...

38:01.730 --> 38:04.298
just tell him
I'll be right back.

38:33.675 --> 38:36.417
Hey! Hey!

38:36.591 --> 38:39.245
What the heck
does that even mean?

38:39.420 --> 38:41.160
Got me.

38:41.335 --> 38:43.249
Could be a statement

38:43.424 --> 38:46.470
as to the underlying
unreliability of time.

38:46.644 --> 38:48.907
Or a testimony

38:49.081 --> 38:52.737
along the lines
of "seize the day."

38:52.911 --> 38:56.088
They don't pay me to write 'em,

38:56.262 --> 38:59.004
just slap 'em up.

38:59.178 --> 39:00.658
Which I did.

39:00.832 --> 39:02.747
And now it's done.

39:04.314 --> 39:08.100
And I find myself once more
at a crossroads,

39:08.274 --> 39:10.320
unemployed.

39:11.452 --> 39:13.410
So I...

39:13.584 --> 39:15.456
suppose for me,

39:15.630 --> 39:17.762
the future I once feared
has arrived,

39:17.936 --> 39:21.723
as predicted
by this very billboard.

39:43.353 --> 39:45.355
♪

40:14.036 --> 40:16.038
[wind whistling]

40:24.089 --> 40:26.440
[door creaking, thudding]

40:53.249 --> 40:55.425
[rattling nearby]

41:20.276 --> 41:22.278
[speaking indistinctly]

41:25.934 --> 41:27.762
[barrel clangs]

41:32.941 --> 41:34.856
[grunts]

41:47.608 --> 41:48.696
[gunshot]

41:50.741 --> 41:52.134
[clicking]

42:14.112 --> 42:16.158
♪

42:39.268 --> 42:41.270
♪

43:04.336 --> 43:06.382
♪

43:25.880 --> 43:27.882
[paws clattering]

43:58.086 --> 44:00.523
♪

44:07.878 --> 44:09.706
MAN:
I am Alpha

44:09.880 --> 44:11.577
and Omega.

44:11.752 --> 44:12.927
The first

44:13.101 --> 44:14.537
and the last.

44:14.711 --> 44:17.105
And what thou seest,

44:17.279 --> 44:18.889
write it in a book

44:19.063 --> 44:21.457
and send it
to the seven churches,

44:21.631 --> 44:24.460
[coughs]
which are in Asia.

44:29.117 --> 44:31.772
[air hissing]

44:31.946 --> 44:34.296
I just woke up.

44:35.558 --> 44:37.386
Come closer.

44:37.560 --> 44:40.432
It smells like rain.

44:40.606 --> 44:42.478
Ah, worry not.

44:42.652 --> 44:45.437
For it is written:
no more flood.

44:45.611 --> 44:47.657
The fire next time.

44:55.447 --> 44:57.362
[air hissing]

44:57.536 --> 44:59.974
I'm-I'm looking for my friend.

45:00.148 --> 45:02.150
I fell asleep.

45:04.152 --> 45:06.589
Come closer.

45:24.259 --> 45:27.175
I... I'm gonna wait in my room.

45:31.919 --> 45:34.182
[man coughing]

46:04.690 --> 46:06.736
♪

46:26.756 --> 46:28.758
[birds squawking outside]

46:51.259 --> 46:53.174
[rapid scratching]

46:53.348 --> 46:55.306
[low growling]

46:55.480 --> 46:56.917
[barks]

46:58.005 --> 46:59.441
[growls]

47:01.095 --> 47:03.837
[barks]

47:10.278 --> 47:12.280
[whining]

47:41.787 --> 47:43.833
♪

48:13.689 --> 48:15.691
♪

50:29.042 --> 50:30.347
MAN:
Now I get it.

50:30.521 --> 50:32.001
[rooster crows]
